column25: Electronic track can be played through a full sound system or something simple such as an iPad and bluetooth speaker.
Score shows timings to line up singing with electronic track. Singers also make bubble sounds with tongue on palette, glissandi, loud whispered syllables.

The aleatoric sections evoke the wonder of seeing fireflies on a summer night, so more silence than sound creates a sparse, transparent texture. The optional percussion part may be played by a triangle, a mark tree, or similar high pitch ringing instrument. The pianist may add some sustain pedal in the more legato passages but most of the texture is lacy and delicate.

column3: For the Toad by the Kitchen Step
column25: Singers are invited to utter gentle vocal fry with different vowels, using their own heartbeat for the tempo. A few singers are invited to step quietly in place, asynchronously, to create the sound of footsteps. The organist may play assorted unpitched mechanical sounds such as pressing/lifting keys and pulling/pushing stops to sound like a noisy craft workshop.

Performance note for live or recorded performance This mostly aleatoric composition is suitable for live or recorded singing along with nature soundtrack. Observe the order of entrances, but know that much of it is not meant to line up exactly. Sing and speak quite expressively. “Flocking the flute” means to sing along closely with the flute line. When singing live, you may wish to create a V-shaped acoustic by starting the flock in the center and staggering the entrances toward the sides. If you are recording, you may flock by slightly staggering the entrances following the flute. Whenever you see a box around a passage, repeat ad libitum until you hear the cue to stop. The recording engineer may add some distortion or other effects.

column25: For live performance, the director may use a timer to cue the entrances. For zoom performance, watch the video to sing together (https://youtu.be/BAkbYolE7W8). This piece employs aleatoric singing in which singers sing independently of one another. Whisper or sing the passage once during the time frame. You choose your own tempo. If you have not finished singing your phrase when the time frame is over, go ahead and finish it so it spills over into the next frame. Even though the text uses Julian's original spelling, you may pronounce it in modern English. Sing in the octave most comfortable for you. The director may wish to organize staggered entrances so the singing is spread out over the time frame. A blue line will appear under each passage during the time to sing. The timer will help you know where you are in the piece. The solo passage in the middle may be sung by an individual for a change of texture and the opportunity to hear the entire text in one passage. It‚Äôs also fine, however, if everyone wants to sing it. To avoid audio feedback, it‚Äôs best for everyone to use headphones or earbuds. It‚Äôs also helpful to adjust output volume levels so everyone is about the same volume. If you‚Äôre singing on Zoom, be sure to share the computer sound so you hear the soundtrack.
